<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>International&#174; T 444E Diesel Engine - Model Years Late 1997 to 2003 - Oil Pan, Vibration Damper, Oil
        Pump Water Pump, And Front Cover - Removal - Vibration Damper
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="install" graphiccount="3">
        <title>Vibration Damper</title>
        <figure id="f1200506" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figf07/f0702.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px" box="yes"/>
            <caption>Checking the Vibration Damper Runout</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Paint Removal Areas (4 locations at 90&#176; intervals)</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Dial Indicator</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Before removing the vibration damper, check the vibration damper runout as follows:</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Pry only in one direction to eliminate any possible error induced by crankshaft end play.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Remove any paint from the face of the vibration damper at four points 90&#176; apart.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Attach a magnetic base dial indicator to the front of the crankcase or oil pan. Position
                    the indicator point on the unpainted surface.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Pry the crankshaft forward and zero the indicator. The zero point is now the baseline.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Turn the crankshaft 90&#176; and pry the crankshaft forward. Record the reading.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Repeat Step d at each unpainted surface. If the runout exceeds specifications, replace
                    vibration damper.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1200507" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figeg3/eg3334.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="240px"
                     scalefitheight="232px" box="yes"/>
            <caption>Removing the Vibration Damper Mounting Bolt</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Vibration Damper</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Washer</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Mounting Bolt</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the vibration damper mounting bolt. Remove the washer and loosely install the
                mounting bolt so the puller does not damage the bolt threads during removal.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <figure id="f1200508" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic filename="../figeg2/eg2597.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="240px"
                     scalefitheight="232px" box="yes"/>
            <caption>Removing the Vibration Damper Assembly</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Vibration Damper</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Puller</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Forcing Screw</callout1>
                <callout1 type="arabic">Removal Bolts (3)</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Mount the vibration damper removal tool to the damper with the three bolts that are
                provided.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Insert the forcing screw and turn it in against the mounting bolt. The vibration damper will
                be pulled off the crankshaft. Remove the mounting bolt and the damper.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
